e formation of European cultural identity between the mid-eighteenth and late nineteenth centuries.Moe examines an exciting range of unfamiliar texts and visual representations including travel writing, political discourse, literary texts, and etchings to illuminate the imaginative geography that shaped the divide between north and south. His narrative moves from a broad examination of the representation of the south in European culture to close readings of the literary works of Leopardi and Giovanni Verga. This groundbreaking investigation into the origins of the modern vision of the Mezzogiorno is made all the more urgent by the emergence of separatism in Italy in the 1990s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPublic opinionzItaly, Northern. 0aStereotypes (Social psychology)zItaly. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  a20th century.  acivic.  acultural history.  acultural identity.  acultural life.  acultural theory.  aeurope.  agiovanni verga.  agovernment and governing.  ahistorians.  ahistoriography.  aideological differences.  aitalian culture.  aitalian history.  aitalian literature.  aitalian politics.  aitalian society.  aitaly.  aleopardi.  amezzogiorno.  anational divides.  anonfiction.  apolitical divides.  apolitical theory.  aseparatism.  asouthern italy.  asouthern question.  atravel writing.  avesuvius.  awestern history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022652440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093982040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939820423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520939820/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  